.TE
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[CR]undefined\f[R] is a property of the \f[I]global object\f[R].
That is, it is a variable in global scope.
.PP
In all non\-legacy browsers, \f[CR]undefined\f[R] is a
non\-configurable, non\-writable property.
Even when this is not the case, avoid overriding it.
.PP
A variable that has not been assigned a value is of type
\f[CR]undefined\f[R].
A function returns \f[CR]undefined\f[R] if a value was not
\f[CR]returned\f[R].
Accessing a property that does not exist also returns
\f[CR]undefined\f[R].
The \f[CR]void\f[R] operator always returns \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] While you can use \f[CR]undefined\f[R] as an identifier
(variable name) in any scope other than the global scope (because
\f[CR]undefined\f[R] is not a reserved word), doing so is a very bad
idea that will make your code difficult to maintain and debug.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// DON\(aqT DO THIS\f[R]

(() \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  \f[B]const\f[R] \f[B]undefined\f[R] = \(dqfoo\(dq;
  console.log(\f[B]undefined\f[R], \f[B]typeof\f[R] \f[B]undefined\f[R]); \f[I]// foo string\f[R]
})();

((\f[B]undefined\f[R]) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.log(\f[B]undefined\f[R], \f[B]typeof\f[R] \f[B]undefined\f[R]); \f[I]// foo string\f[R]
})(\(dqfoo\(dq);
.EE
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Strict equality and undefined
You can use \f[CR]undefined\f[R] and the strict equality and inequality
operators to determine whether a variable has a value.
In the following code, the variable \f[CR]x\f[R] is not initialized, and
the \f[CR]if\f[R] statement evaluates to true.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] x;
\f[B]if\f[R] (x === \f[B]undefined\f[R]) {
  \f[I]// these statements execute\f[R]
} \f[B]else\f[R] {
  \f[I]// these statements do not execute\f[R]
}
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] The \f[I]strict equality\f[R] operator (as opposed to
the \f[I]loose equality\f[R] operator) must be used here, because
\f[CR]x == undefined\f[R] also checks whether \f[CR]x\f[R] is
\f[CR]null\f[R], while strict equality doesn\(cqt.
This is because \f[CR]null\f[R] is not equivalent to
\f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.PP
See Equality comparison and sameness for details.
.RE
.SS typeof operator and undefined
\f[CR]typeof\f[R] can also determine whether a variable is
\f[CR]undefined\f[R]:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] x;
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] x === \(dqundefined\(dq) {
  \f[I]// these statements execute\f[R]
}
.EE
.PP
One reason to use \f[CR]typeof\f[R] is that it does not throw an error
if the variable does not exist in the current scope.
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// x has not been declared before\f[R]
\f[I]// evaluates to true without errors\f[R]
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] x === \(dqundefined\(dq) {
  \f[I]// these statements execute\f[R]
}

\f[I]// Throws a ReferenceError\f[R]
\f[B]if\f[R] (x === \f[B]undefined\f[R]) {
}
.EE
.PP
It also works with variables declared with \f[CR]var\f[R]
\f[I]after\f[R] the check, because the declaration is hoisted to the top
of the scope with value \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] x === \(dqundefined\(dq) {
  \f[I]// these statements execute\f[R]
}
\f[B]var\f[R] x = 1;
.EE
.PP
This technique is usually only useful for testing global variables.
You can know if a variable exists at any other scope (blocks, functions,
modules, etc.)
just by looking at the source code.
The global scope is bound to the global object, so checking the
existence of a variable in the global context can be done by checking
the existence of a property on the \f[I]global object\f[R], such as by
using the \f[CR]in\f[R] operator:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\(dqx\(dq \f[B]in\f[R] window) {
  \f[I]// These statements execute only if x is defined globally\f[R]
}
.EE
.PP
However, none of the techniques above work if the variable is declared
with \f[CR]let\f[R], \f[CR]const\f[R], or other lexical declarations.
Using \f[CR]typeof\f[R] before the line of declaration still produces a
\f[CR]ReferenceError\f[R], due to the temporal dead zone (TDZ).
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] z === \(dqundefined\(dq) {
  \f[I]// Uncaught ReferenceError: Cannot access \(aqz\(aq before initialization\f[R]
}
\f[B]let\f[R] z = 1;
.EE
.PP
Furthermore, \f[CR]let\f[R] and \f[CR]const\f[R] declarations do not
create properties on the global object, so they cannot be checked with
the \f[CR]in\f[R] operator either.
.PP
\f[B]Bad\f[R]
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] z;
\f[B]if\f[R] (\(dqz\(dq \f[B]in\f[R] window) {
  \f[I]// false, even if z is declared globally with let or const\f[R]
}
.EE
.PP
If you want to share global variables across different scripts, it is
more advisable to use \f[CR]var\f[R] or explicitly attach them to the
global object:
.IP
.EX
window.myGlobalVar = \(dqfoo\(dq;
.EE
.SS void operator and undefined
The \f[CR]void\f[R] operator can also be used to produce the
\f[CR]undefined\f[R] value.
This is very commonly seen in minified code because \f[CR]void 0\f[R] is
3 bytes shorter and cannot be overridden.
You should usually avoid this pattern in your own code.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] x;
\f[B]if\f[R] (x === \f[B]void\f[R] 0) {
  \f[I]// these statements execute\f[R]
}

\f[I]// y has not been declared before\f[R]
\f[B]if\f[R] (y === \f[B]void\f[R] 0) {
  \f[I]// throws Uncaught ReferenceError: y is not defined\f[R]
}
.EE
